# Per-file merge strategies.
#
# `merge=union` keeps BOTH sides of every conflict block in the named
# files. We apply it to two collaboration choke-points whose conflicts
# are always false positives at the semantic level:
#
# - `CHANGELOG.md` — every feature PR inserts a new bullet at the top
#   of `## Unreleased`. Two PRs inserting at the same anchor produce a
#   text-level conflict that git's default merge cannot resolve, even
#   though the right answer is always "keep both entries". Union merge
#   does exactly that.
#
# - `planning/next.md` — the M1/M2/M3 work-tracker tables pack rows
#   tightly with no blank lines, so two PRs each deleting a different
#   row land inside the same 3-line context window and conflict. Union
#   merge keeps both rows; the row each PR meant to delete just lingers
#   for one extra cycle until a doc-sync sweep removes it. Strictly
#   better than the current state where six in-flight PRs all go DIRTY
#   the moment one of them merges.
#
# Drawback to know: union-merged conflicts are silently resolved by
# concatenation, so a deliberate row-rewrite (one branch reword, the
# other branch deletes) loses the deletion. The only thing that gets
# reliably merged in either of these files is appends and deletes —
# rewrites need a manual pass at PR-author time, which is fine.
CHANGELOG.md     merge=union
planning/next.md merge=union
